05711nam a22007455i 9780812295665DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122956657 a10.9783/97808122956652doi  a(DE-B1597)521536  a(OCoLC)1143793256  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHG2481b.R674 2019 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a330.973/09312231 aRose, Mark H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarket Rules :bBankers, Presidents, and the Origins of the Great Recession /cMark H. Rose. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Business, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Politics and the Markets They Made -- tPART I. LAWMAKERS AND REGULATORS -- tChapter 1. Deregulation Before Deregulation: John Kennedy, Lyndon Johnson, and James Saxon -- tChapter 2. Supermarket Banks: Richard Nixon and Donald Regan -- tPART II. BANKERS IN POLITICS -- tChapter 3. Rescuing Banks Through Growth: Walter Wriston and Citicorp -- tChapter 4. A Marine in Banker’s Clothing: Hugh McColl and North Carolina National Bank -- tPART III. NEW REGIMES FOR BANKERS -- tChapter 5. Full-Service Banks: Bill Clinton and Sandy Weill -- tChapter 6. God’s Work in Finance: Ken Lewis, Charles Prince, Richard Fuld, and Henry Paulson -- tChapter 7. Reregulating the Regulators: Barack Obama and Timothy Geithner -- tEpilogue. Another Round of Bank Politics -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough most Americans attribute shifting practices in the financial industry to the invisible hand of the market, Mark H. Rose reveals the degree to which presidents, legislators, regulators, and even bankers themselves have long taken an active interest in regulating the industry.In 1971, members of Richard Nixon's Commission on Financial Structure and Regulation described the banks they sought to create as "supermarkets." Analogous to the twentieth-century model of a store at which Americans could buy everything from soft drinks to fresh produce, supermarket banks would accept deposits, make loans, sell insurance, guide mergers and acquisitions, and underwrite stock and bond issues. The supermarket bank presented a radical departure from the financial industry as it stood, composed as it was of local savings and loans, commercial banks, investment banks, mutual funds, and insurance firms. Over the next four decades, through a process Rose describes as "grinding politics," supermarket banks became the guiding model of the financial industry. As the banking industry consolidated, it grew too large while remaining too fragmented and unwieldy for politicians to regulate and for regulators to understand—until, in 2008, those supermarket banks, such as Citigroup, needed federal help to survive and prosper once again.Rose explains the history of the financial industry as a story of individuals—some well-known, like Presidents Kennedy, Carter, Reagan, and Clinton; Treasury Secretaries Donald Regan and Timothy Geithner; and JP Morgan CEO Jamie Dimon; and some less so, though equally influential, such as Kennedy's Comptroller of the Currency James J. Saxon, Citicorp CEO Walter Wriston, and Bank of America CEOs Hugh McColl and Kenneth Lewis. Rose traces the evolution of supermarket banks from the early days of the Kennedy administration, through the financial crisis of 2008, and up to the Trump administration's attempts to modify bank rules. Deeply researched and accessibly written, Market Rules demystifies the major trends in the banking industry and brings financial policy to life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF t